    (1,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The IPKF (Indian Peace Keeping Force) was deployed in Sri Lanka during whose tenure to enforce peace after which agreement?','Indira Gandhi — Simla Pact','Rajiv Gandhi — India-Sri Lanka Accord (1987)','Narasimha Rao — SAARC Agreement','Vajpayee — Colombo Declaration','b','The IPKF was deployed in Sri Lanka following the India-Sri Lanka Accord signed by Rajiv Gandhi and Sri Lankan President Jayewardene in July 1987. The IPKF was supposed to disarm LTTE (Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam) but got embroiled in conflict. Rajiv Gandhi was later assassinated by an LTTE suicide bomber in 1991.'),
    (1,'easy','పోఖ్రాన్ అణు పరీక్ష ఎప్పుడు? / Pokhran II ("Operation Shakti") nuclear tests were conducted in which year under which PM?','1974 — Indira Gandhi','1996 — Deve Gowda','1998 — Atal Bihari Vajpayee','2004 — Manmohan Singh','c','India conducted five nuclear tests at Pokhran, Rajasthan, in May 1998 under PM Atal Bihari Vajpayee, codenamed "Operation Shakti." India declared itself a nuclear weapons state. The US and other countries imposed brief sanctions.'),
    (1,'hard','భారత అణు సిద్ధాంతం ఏమిటి? / India\'s No First Use (NFU) nuclear policy means:','India will not test nuclear weapons first','India will not be the first to use nuclear weapons in a conflict; will use only in retaliation to nuclear attack','India will not share nuclear technology with other countries','India will not use nuclear weapons against non-nuclear states','b','India\'s No First Use (NFU) policy, declared after the May 1998 Pokhran II tests, states that India will not be the first country to use nuclear weapons in any conflict. Nuclear weapons will only be used in retaliation against a nuclear attack on Indian territory or against Indian forces anywhere.'),

    # Section 2: Non-Alignment and Panchsheel (8)
    (2,'easy','పంచశీల సూత్రాలు ఏది? / Panchsheel (Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence) was first articulated in which agreement?','Bandung Declaration 1955','India-China Agreement on Trade and Intercourse with Tibet Region 1954','NAM Charter 1961','SAARC Charter 1985','b','Panchsheel was first formally incorporated in the "Agreement between the Republic of India and the People\'s Republic of China on Trade and Intercourse between Tibet Region of China and India," signed on April 29, 1954, in Beijing.'),
    (2,'easy','పంచశీల సూత్రాలు ఏది? / Which of the following is NOT one of the Five Principles of Panchsheel?','Mutual respect for territorial integrity and sovereignty','Non-interference in internal affairs','Mutual defence alliance obligations','Peaceful coexistence','c','The Five Principles of Panchsheel are: (1) mutual respect for territorial integrity/sovereignty, (2) mutual non-aggression, (3) mutual non-interference in internal affairs, (4) equality and mutual benefit, (5) peaceful coexistence. Mutual defence alliance obligations are NOT part of Panchsheel.'),
    (2,'medium','NAM జతకట్టని ఉద్యమం ఎంత? / The Bandung Conference (1955) which laid the groundwork for NAM was attended by how many Asian and African nations?','15','21','29','44','c','The Bandung Conference (April 1955) in Bandung, Indonesia, was attended by 29 Asian and African nations. It was a landmark in the movement for decolonisation and non-alignment, bringing together leaders like Nehru, Nasser, Sukarno, Chou En-lai, and others.'),
    (2,'easy','NAM జతకట్టని ఉద్యమం ఏది? / The Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) was formally founded at which conference and in which city?','Bandung Conference 1955','Belgrade Conference 1961','Cairo Summit 1964','Lusaka Summit 1970','b','NAM was formally founded at the First Summit Conference in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in September 1961. The founding fathers were: Nehru (India), Nasser (Egypt), Tito (Yugoslavia), Sukarno (Indonesia), and Nkrumah (Ghana).'),
    (2,'medium','NAM జతకట్టని ఉద్యమం ఎప్పుడు? / India hosted the NAM Summit in New Delhi in which year?','1961','1970','1983','1992','c','India hosted the Seventh NAM Summit in New Delhi in 1983 under PM Indira Gandhi. India was a prominent member and leader within NAM throughout the Cold War period.'),
    (2,'hard','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఎంత? / NAM\'s current membership is approximately how many countries?','25','60','90','120','d','NAM currently has approximately 120 member states and 17 observer states. Most of the world\'s developing countries are NAM members, making it one of the largest international organisations after the United Nations.'),
    (2,'easy','QUAD కూటమి ఏది? / The QUAD (Quadrilateral Security Dialogue) involves which four countries?','India, USA, UK, Australia','India, USA, Japan, Australia','India, USA, France, Japan','India, USA, Israel, UAE','b','The QUAD (Quadrilateral Security Dialogue) involves India, the United States, Japan, and Australia. Originally formed in 2007, it was revived in 2017 and elevated to a leaders\' level dialogue in 2021, focused on a free and open Indo-Pacific.'),
    (2,'medium','భారత-రష్యా సంబంధాలు ఏది? / India\'s abstention on UN Security Council and General Assembly resolutions condemning Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine (2022) reflected which foreign policy principle?','Pro-Russia alignment','Strategic autonomy — independent decision-making, not locking into any bloc','Anti-Western stance','NAM obligation to support smaller countries','b','India\'s abstention reflected its strategic autonomy — the principle of making independent decisions based on India\'s national interest rather than aligning with any bloc. India has deep defence ties with Russia (S-400, arms) and did not want to antagonise Russia while also not endorsing the invasion.'),

    # Section 3: Neighbours (8)
    (3,'easy','SAARC సహకారం ఎప్పుడు? / SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) was founded in which year and has its headquarters in which city?','1980 — New Delhi','1985 — Kathmandu, Nepal','1990 — Dhaka','1992 — Islamabad','b','SAARC was founded at the First SAARC Summit in Dhaka on December 8, 1985. Its Secretariat is located in Kathmandu, Nepal. It has 8 member states: India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan, Maldives, and Afghanistan.'),
    (3,'medium','SAARC సహకారం ఏది? / India boycotted the 2016 SAARC Summit (scheduled in Islamabad) following which events?','India-China border clash','Pathankot airbase attack (January 2016) and Uri attack (September 2016) — cross-border terrorism','Bangladesh political crisis','Nepal\'s new constitution dispute','b','India boycotted the 19th SAARC Summit scheduled for Islamabad in 2016 following the Pathankot airbase attack (January 2016) and Uri attack (September 2016) attributed to Pakistan-sponsored terrorist groups. The summit was called off after India, Bangladesh, Bhutan, and Afghanistan also withdrew.'),
    (3,'easy','SAARC సహకారం ఏమిటి? / BIMSTEC (Bay of Bengal Initiative for Multi-Sectoral Technical and Economic Cooperation) is India\'s alternative mechanism to SAARC primarily because:','SAARC excluded Nepal','Pakistan is not a BIMSTEC member — BIMSTEC focuses on Bay of Bengal littoral states + Thailand, Myanmar, without Pakistan','BIMSTEC has a better record on climate change','India chairs BIMSTEC','b','BIMSTEC (India, Bangladesh, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, Thailand, Nepal, Bhutan) is significant because it includes all major South Asian economies EXCEPT Pakistan, allowing cooperation to proceed without being blocked by the India-Pakistan dispute as SAARC has been.'),
    (3,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఎప్పుడు? / The Galwan Valley clash between Indian and Chinese troops occurred in which year, resulting in casualties?','2017','2019','2020','2021','c','The Galwan Valley clash occurred on June 15, 2020, in the Galwan River Valley in Ladakh (LAC area). It resulted in the death of 20 Indian soldiers and casualties on the Chinese side — the first deadly clash on the LAC since 1975.'),
    (3,'hard','భారత-చైనా సంబంధాలు ఏమిటి? / India refused to join China\'s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI) primarily because:','India cannot afford BRI membership fees','The China-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC) passes through Pakistan-Occupied Kashmir (POK), which India considers its territory','India prefers the QUAD over BRI','India already has its own equivalent initiative','b','India\'s main objection to the BRI is that the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor (CPEC) — BRI\'s flagship project — passes through Gilgit-Baltistan (Pakistan-Occupied Kashmir/POK), which India claims as part of its sovereign territory of Jammu & Kashmir.'),
    (3,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The India-Sri Lanka Accord (1987) resulted in the deployment of the Indian Peace Keeping Force (IPKF) to deal with which issue?','Sri Lanka-India maritime boundary dispute','Tamil separatist conflict (LTTE) in Sri Lanka','Sri Lanka\'s nuclear programme','Economic dispute over fishermen rights','b','The India-Sri Lanka Accord (Rajiv Gandhi-Jayewardene, July 1987) aimed to address the Tamil ethnic conflict in Sri Lanka. It resulted in IPKF deployment to disarm the LTTE and implement a ceasefire. The IPKF was withdrawn in 1990 under PM V.P. Singh after suffering heavy casualties.'),
    (3,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / India signed the Land Boundary Agreement (LBA) with Bangladesh in 2015, resolving the issue of:','Maritime boundaries in Bay of Bengal','Enclaves (chhitmahal) — exchange of enclaved territories between India and Bangladesh','Rohingya refugee crisis','Farakka Barrage water sharing','b','The India-Bangladesh Land Boundary Agreement (LBA) was ratified by India in May 2015 (through the 100th Constitutional Amendment), resolving the long-standing issue of enclaves (chhitmahal) — small pockets of Indian territory inside Bangladesh and vice versa, which had left thousands of people stateless.'),
    (3,'hard','భారత-చైనా సంబంధాలు ఏమిటి? / The Doklam standoff (June-August 2017) involved India intervening to stop road construction by China in a territory disputed between:','India and China','China and Nepal','China and Bhutan, with India intervening in support of Bhutan','Pakistan and China','c','The Doklam standoff arose when China began constructing a road in the Doklam plateau — an area disputed between China and Bhutan. India intervened citing the 1949 India-Bhutan Treaty of Friendship which obligates India to maintain Bhutan\'s security. After 73 days, both sides disengaged.'),

    # Section 4: Major Powers (8)
    (4,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / The Indo-US Civil Nuclear Deal (2008) is also known as:','The Lahore Declaration','The 123 Agreement','The Strategic Partnership Agreement','The NSSP Agreement','b','The Indo-US Civil Nuclear Deal is formally called the 123 Agreement — named after Section 123 of the US Atomic Energy Act 1954 which governs nuclear cooperation agreements. It was signed in October 2008 under PM Manmohan Singh and President George W. Bush.'),
    (4,'medium','పోఖ్రాన్ అణు పరీక్ష ఏమిటి? / The US sanctions imposed on India after Pokhran II (1998) were lifted primarily because of:','India signing the NPT','The September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks — US needed India\'s cooperation; sanctions were strategically counterproductive','India giving up its nuclear programme','India\'s economic reforms impressing the US','b','The US initially imposed Glenn Amendment sanctions on India after the 1998 Pokhran II tests. Most sanctions were lifted after the 9/11 attacks (2001) made India a crucial partner in the "War on Terror." The broader strategic partnership — culminating in the 2008 nuclear deal — followed.'),
    (4,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఎప్పుడు? / India joined the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO) as a full member in which year?','2005','2010','2015','2017','d','India (and Pakistan) became full members of the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO) at the Astana, Kazakhstan summit in June 2017. The SCO is a Eurasian security and economic organisation dominated by Russia and China.'),
    (4,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / LEMOA (Logistics Exchange Memorandum of Agreement), signed between India and the USA in 2016, allows:','Nuclear warhead transfer','Mutual use of each other\'s military logistics facilities (bases, ports, airfields) for refuelling and resupply','Joint nuclear command','India to purchase nuclear weapons from US','b','LEMOA (Logistics Exchange Memorandum of Agreement), signed in August 2016, allows India and the US military to use each other\'s land, air, and naval facilities for refuelling and logistics support. It does not allow permanent basing but facilitates interoperability.'),
    (4,'hard','భారత-రష్యా సంబంధాలు ఏమిటి? / India purchased the S-400 Triumf long-range surface-to-air missile defence system from Russia despite the threat of US CAATSA sanctions (Countering America\'s Adversaries Through Sanctions Act). This decision reflects:','India\'s alignment with Russia over the US','India\'s strategic autonomy — making defence decisions based on national security needs regardless of pressure from any power','India\'s rejection of all US defence ties','India\'s nuclear agreement with Russia','b','India\'s decision to proceed with S-400 purchase despite CAATSA threats illustrates strategic autonomy — India prioritised its air defence needs (the S-400 is highly capable against Pakistani and Chinese missiles/aircraft) over US demands. The Biden administration ultimately waived CAATSA sanctions against India.'),
    (4,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The BrahMos missile is a joint venture between India and which country?','USA','France','Russia','Israel','c','BrahMos is a supersonic cruise missile jointly developed by India\'s DRDO and Russia\'s NPO Mashinostroyeniya. "BrahMos" = Brahmaputra (India) + Moskva (Russia). It is currently the world\'s fastest operational supersonic cruise missile.'),
    (4,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / I2U2 (India-Israel-UAE-USA) is a grouping focused on which region?','Europe','Central Asia','West Asia and clean energy/infrastructure cooperation','Arctic','c','I2U2 (referred to as the "West Asian Quad") was formed in 2021 and focuses on West Asia (Middle East). The grouping aims at cooperation on infrastructure, clean energy, water, space, health, and food security in West Asia and beyond.'),
    (4,'hard','Look East విధానం ఏమిటి? / India\'s "Act East Policy" under PM Modi (2014) upgraded the earlier "Look East Policy" by:','Changing it from economic engagement to security engagement only','Expanding from ASEAN-centric engagement to include Japan, South Korea, Australia; elevating focus to strategic and security dimensions beyond economics','Withdrawing from ASEAN engagement','Replacing ASEAN with QUAD','b','The Act East Policy upgraded Look East by: (1) expanding geographic scope beyond ASEAN to include Japan, Australia, South Korea, and the Pacific; (2) elevating the engagement from primarily economic to include security/strategic dimensions; (3) bringing ASEAN to the forefront of India\'s foreign policy with annual India-ASEAN summits and the QUAD partnership.'),

    # Section 5: Multilateral (8)
    (5,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / India is a founding member of which international organisation established in 1945?','World Trade Organisation (WTO)','International Monetary Fund (IMF)','United Nations (UN)','Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)','c','India is a founding member of the United Nations, having signed the UN Charter in San Francisco in June 1945. India is also a founding member of the IMF and World Bank (Bretton Woods institutions).'),
    (5,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / India has been historically one of the largest contributors of troops to which UN mission type?','UN Security Council permanent missions','UN Peacekeeping Missions (UNPKF)','UN Humanitarian Aid missions','UN Sanctions enforcement','b','India is historically one of the largest contributors of troops to UN Peacekeeping Missions (UNPKF). Tens of thousands of Indian soldiers, police, and civilians have served in UN peacekeeping operations across the world since 1950.'),
    (5,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The International Solar Alliance (ISA) was launched as an initiative of which two countries and formally founded where?','USA and China — New York','India and France — COP21, Paris (2015)','India and Germany — Bonn','UK and India — London','b','The International Solar Alliance (ISA) was launched jointly by PM Modi and French President Hollande at COP21 in Paris on November 30, 2015. The ISA Framework Agreement was opened for signature in 2016. The ISA HQ is in Gurugram, India.'),
    (5,'medium','G20 వేదిక ఎప్పుడు? / India held the G20 Presidency in which year and hosted the G20 Summit under which theme?','2021 — "Unite for Our Planet"','2022–23 — "Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam (One Earth One Family One Future)"','2019 — "Shaping an Interconnected World"','2018 — "Building Consensus for Fair and Sustainable Development"','b','India held the G20 Presidency from December 1, 2022 to November 30, 2023, under the theme "Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam — One Earth, One Family, One Future." The G20 Leaders\' Summit was held in New Delhi on September 9–10, 2023.'),
    (5,'hard','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / India is seeking a permanent seat on the UN Security Council (UNSC). The G4 grouping that advocates for UNSC expansion includes:','India, China, Russia, Brazil','India, Brazil, Germany, Japan','India, Australia, Japan, Germany','India, France, UK, Germany','b','G4 (Group of Four) nations — India, Brazil, Germany, and Japan — collectively advocate for expanding the UNSC to include permanent seats. They support each other\'s candidacy for permanent membership and are the main candidates for the proposed new permanent seats.'),
    (5,'easy','అణు అప్రసార ఒప్పందం ఏది? / India has NOT signed which two international nuclear non-proliferation treaties?','IAEA safeguards and CTBT','NPT (Non-Proliferation Treaty) and CTBT (Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty)','START and New START','NPT and MTCR','b','India has not signed the NPT (Non-Proliferation Treaty) — arguing it is discriminatory as it divides the world into nuclear and non-nuclear states. India has also not signed the CTBT (Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty). India has its own nuclear doctrine (NFU + credible minimum deterrence).'),
    (5,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఎప్పుడు? / India joined MTCR (Missile Technology Control Regime) in which year?','2008','2012','2016','2019','c','India was admitted to MTCR (Missile Technology Control Regime) in June 2016. MTCR is an informal grouping that controls the export of missiles and related technologies. India\'s membership strengthens its export control credentials.'),
    (5,'hard','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The Coalition for Disaster Resilient Infrastructure (CDRI), launched by India, focuses on which aspect of climate resilience?','Reducing carbon emissions only','Building disaster and climate-resilient infrastructure, particularly in developing countries','Nuclear energy transition','Coastal erosion prevention only','b','CDRI (Coalition for Disaster Resilient Infrastructure) was launched by PM Modi at the UN General Assembly in September 2019. It focuses on promoting climate-resilient infrastructure through knowledge sharing, funding, and technical assistance to developing countries. India and the UK are co-chairs.'),

    # Section 6: Post-Cold War (8)
    (6,'easy','Look East విధానం ఎప్పుడు? / The Act East Policy, which renamed and upgraded the Look East Policy, was announced by which PM in which year?','Manmohan Singh in 2009','Narendra Modi in 2014','Rajiv Gandhi in 1989','Atal Bihari Vajpayee in 2002','b','PM Narendra Modi renamed and upgraded the "Look East Policy" to "Act East Policy" in November 2014 at the ASEAN-India Summit in Naypyidaw, Myanmar. The Act East Policy signifies a shift from passive engagement to active, multidimensional engagement with East and Southeast Asia.'),
    (6,'medium','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / SAGAR, India\'s vision for the Indian Ocean, stands for:','Strategic Alliance for Growth and Regional Diplomacy','Security and Growth for All in the Region','South Asian Geopolitics and Regional Strategy','Special Autonomous Governance and Regional Relations','b','SAGAR (Security and Growth for All in the Region) is PM Modi\'s vision for the Indian Ocean articulated in March 2015 during a visit to Mauritius. It aims at deepening economic and security cooperation with Indian Ocean island nations and maintaining a free, open, and rules-based Indo-Pacific.'),
    (6,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The United Nations General Assembly adopted a resolution declaring June 21 as the International Day of Yoga following a proposal by which country?','France','USA','India','Japan','c','India proposed the International Day of Yoga at the UN General Assembly (UNGA) in 2014, and the UNGA unanimously adopted the resolution in December 2014, declaring June 21 as International Day of Yoga. This has become part of India\'s "yoga diplomacy."'),
    (6,'medium','పొరుగు దేశాల విధానం ఏమిటి? / The "Neighbourhood First" policy of the Modi government was symbolically demonstrated by:','India joining SAARC Free Trade Agreement','PM Modi inviting all SAARC leaders to his swearing-in ceremony on May 26, 2014','India providing military aid to all SAARC members','India opening visa-free access to all South Asian neighbours','b','PM Modi\'s "Neighbourhood First" policy was symbolically launched by inviting all SAARC leaders to his swearing-in ceremony on May 26, 2014 — a gesture of prioritising regional relationships. This was followed by bilateral visits to Bhutan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Bangladesh, etc. in the first year.'),
    (6,'hard','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / The Voice of the Global South Summit (2023), hosted by India, was intended to:','Formally expand BRICS membership','Articulate the development and climate priorities of developing countries ahead of G20 — positioning India as voice of the Global South','Replace SAARC with a new organisation','Address only South Asian security concerns','b','India hosted the Voice of the Global South Summit (virtual) in January 2023 and November 2023 to consult with developing countries on issues related to food security, energy security, climate finance, and debt. It was a strategic move by India to position itself as a leader of the Global South in the G20.'),
    (6,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏమిటి? / Pravasi Bharatiya Divas (Non-Resident Indians\' Day) is observed on January 9 to commemorate:','Birth anniversary of Rajiv Gandhi','Day Mahatma Gandhi returned to India from South Africa in 1915','India\'s first ambassador to the UN taking charge','Day Indian diaspora first formed a major organisation','b','Pravasi Bharatiya Divas is observed on January 9 because on January 9, 1915, Mahatma Gandhi returned to India from South Africa where he had spent 21 years fighting for the rights of the Indian community. It celebrates the Indian diaspora\'s contribution to India.'),
    (6,'medium','G20 వేదిక ఏది? / India\'s G20 presidency (2022–23) theme "Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam" comes from which source?','Arthashastra by Kautilya','Maha Upanishad (ancient Sanskrit text) — meaning "One Earth One Family One Future"','Rigveda','Bhagavad Gita','b','Vasudhaiva Kutumbakam (the world is one family) comes from the Maha Upanishad, an ancient Sanskrit text. India used this as the G20 2023 theme, with the full tagline "One Earth, One Family, One Future," emphasising India\'s civilisational vision of global unity.'),
    (6,'hard','భారత-రష్యా సంబంధాలు ఏమిటి? / India\'s decision to significantly increase purchase of Russian crude oil after Russia\'s Ukraine invasion (2022) primarily reflects:','Pro-Russia military alignment','Economic rationality — Russian oil offered at a discount; India\'s energy security trumped Western pressure','India joining Russian-led international organisations','India opposing Ukraine\'s sovereignty','b','India dramatically increased its purchase of discounted Russian crude oil after Western sanctions cut European markets for Russia. This decision was driven by economic interests (cheaper oil for India\'s energy security) and strategic autonomy, not ideological alignment with Russia.'),

    # Section 7: Key Facts (8)
    (7,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / Which article of the Indian Constitution empowers Parliament to make laws implementing international treaties, even if the subject is in the State List?','Article 248','Article 249','Article 253','Article 256','c','Article 253 empowers Parliament to make legislation for implementing international treaties, agreements, or conventions — even if the subject matter falls under the State List (List II) of the Seventh Schedule. This is an exception to the federal division of powers.'),
    (7,'medium','తాష్కెంట్ ఒప్పందం ఏది? / The Tashkent Agreement (1966) ended which conflict and was signed between India and Pakistan with Soviet mediation?','1965 India-Pakistan War','1947–48 Kashmir War','1971 Bangladesh Liberation War','Kargil War 1999','a','The Tashkent Agreement was signed on January 10, 1966, between PM Lal Bahadur Shastri and Pakistani PM Ayub Khan, mediated by Soviet Premier Alexei Kosygin, ending the 1965 India-Pakistan War. Shastri died of a heart attack in Tashkent the next day (January 11, 1966).'),
    (7,'easy','G20 వేదిక ఏది? / India is a founding member of G20. India held the G20 presidency and hosted the summit in which city in September 2023?','Mumbai','Bangalore','New Delhi','Chennai','c','India held the G20 presidency from December 2022 to November 2023 and hosted the G20 Leaders\' Summit at Bharat Mandapam, New Delhi (Pragati Maidan), on September 9–10, 2023.'),
    (7,'hard','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఏది? / The 100th Constitutional Amendment Act (2015) was related to which foreign policy achievement?','Indo-US nuclear deal','India-Bangladesh Land Boundary Agreement (exchange of enclaves)','India-China Line of Actual Control Agreement','India-Pakistan Indus Waters Treaty','b','The 100th Constitutional Amendment Act 2015 was needed to ratify and give effect to the India-Bangladesh Land Boundary Agreement (LBA) — the exchange of 162 enclaves between the two countries. The amendment was required because it involved ceding Indian territories to Bangladesh.'),
    (7,'easy','భారత-పాకిస్తాన్ సంబంధాలు ఏది? / Which event (attack) directly led to the Mumbai 26/11 attacks that severely damaged India-Pakistan relations?','India bombing Pakistan-backed militant camp','LeT (Lashkar-e-Taiba) militants launched a coordinated attack on multiple sites in Mumbai killing 166 people','India-US nuclear deal','India joining QUAD','b','The Mumbai attacks of November 26, 2008 (26/11), were carried out by 10 Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT) militants from Pakistan. The 60-hour siege killed 166 people including foreign nationals. The attacks led India to suspend the composite dialogue with Pakistan.'),
    (7,'medium','QUAD కూటమి ఏది? / The QUAD (Quadrilateral Security Dialogue) was originally formed in 2007 under which context?','China\'s rapid military build-up','Response to the 2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami — the four countries coordinated relief operations','US invasion of Afghanistan','India-Pakistan tensions','b','The QUAD was originally formed in 2007, inspired by the successful coordination between India, the US, Japan, and Australia during the 2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami relief operations. The initiative was primarily driven by Japanese PM Shinzo Abe. It was initially suspended in 2008 due to Australian concerns about antagonising China.'),
    (7,'easy','విదేశాంగ విధానం ఎప్పుడు? / India\'s principal anti-terrorism law, the UAPA (Unlawful Activities Prevention Act), was significantly amended in which year to include the provision of designating individuals (not just organisations) as terrorists?','2004','2008','2013','2019','d','The UAPA was amended in 2019 to include the power to designate individuals as terrorists (in addition to organisations), allowing the government to freeze assets and impose travel restrictions on designated individuals without a court process.'),
